    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{\frac{r}{r^{2}-100}-\frac{1}{r^{2}-100}}}{{\frac{1}{r+100}}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{\left(r-1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+100\right)}{\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)}, r\ne -100</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{\frac{r}{r^{2}-100}-\frac{1}{r^{2}-100}}}{{\frac{1}{r+100}}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{\frac{r}{r^{2}-100}-\frac{1}{r^{2}-100}}</m> and <m>{\frac{1}{r+100}}</m>, which is <m>{\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+100\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{\frac{r}{r^{2}-100}-\frac{1}{r^{2}-100}}}{{\frac{1}{r+100}}} \amp = \frac{{\frac{r}{\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)}-\frac{1}{\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)}}}{{\frac{1}{r+100}}} \\
    \amp = \frac{({\frac{r}{\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)}-\frac{1}{\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)}})\cdot{\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+100\right)}}{({\frac{1}{r+100}})\cdot{\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+100\right)}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{\frac{r}{\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)}\mathopen{}\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+100\right)-\frac{1}{\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)}\mathopen{}\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+100\right)}}{{\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)}}, r \ne -100 \\
    \amp = \frac{{r\mathopen{}\left(r+100\right)-\left(r+100\right)}}{{\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)}}, r \ne -100\\
    \amp = \frac{{r^{2}+99r-100}}{{\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)}}, r \ne -100 \\
    \amp = {\frac{\left(r-1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+100\right)}{\left(r+10\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)}, r\ne -100}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since <m>r+100</m> was canceled, <m>r \ne -100</m> is a lost domain condition.</p>
<p>Although <m>r-10</m> and <m>r + 10</m> were also canceled, <m>r \ne 10</m> and <m>r \ne -10</m> are not lost domain conditions because they are implied in the solution.</p>
</solution>
